<exercise component="proteus" label="proteus-matching-ln-e"  xml:id="proteus-matching-ln-e">
<!--  <title>Matching Problem, Derivatives</title>
  <idx>matching derivatives</idx>
-->
  <statement>
    <p>
      Recall that when we write <q><m>\ln(5)</m></q>, this means <q>the power to which we raise <m>e</m> in order to get 5</q>.  That is, writing <m>z = \ln(5)</m> <em>is saying the exact same thing as</em> <m>e^z = 5</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>f(x) = e^x</m> and <m>g(y)=\ln(y)</m>.  For each of the expressions on the left below, drag the expression onto the equivalent simpler expression on the right.   
    </p>
  </statement>
  <matches>
    <match>
    <premise order="1"><m>\ln(1)</m></premise>
    <response><m>0</m></response>
    </match>
    <match>
    <premise order="4"><m>e^0</m></premise>
    <response><m>1</m></response>
    </match>
    <match>
    <premise  order="2"><m>\ln(e^x)</m></premise>
    <response><m>x</m></response>
    </match>
    <match>
    <premise order="5"><m>e^{\ln(x^5)}</m></premise>
    <response><m>x^5</m></response>
    </match>
    <match>
    <premise order="7"><m>\ln(x^5)</m></premise>
    <response><m>5 \ln(x)</m></response>
    </match>   
    <match>
    <premise order="3"><m>e^{\ln(y)}</m></premise>
    <response><m>y</m></response>
    </match>
    <match>
      <premise order="6"><m>\ln(0)</m></premise>  
      <response>is undefined</response>
    </match>
  </matches>
</exercise>

